==Government==
[[File:Alicante Spain townhall.jpg|thumb|right|Alicante City Hall]]

[[Sonia Castedo]] (born in 1971) is the mayor of the city. She was elected for the post in an extraordinary plenary of the Alicante City Council on September 17, 2008, following resignation of [[Luis Díaz Alperi]]. She is the first woman ever to occupy this position.&lt;ref&gt;http://ecodiario.eleconomista.es/espana/noticias/755344/09/08/Sonia-Castedo-toma-posesion-como-alcaldesa-de-Alicante-la-primera-mujer-en-ocupar-el-cargo-y-demanda-inversiones.html&lt;/ref&gt;

In the latest municipal elections of May 2011, [[Sonia Castedo]] (1971) of the [[People's Party (Spain)|People's Party]] (''Partido Popular'') won the elections with an [[absolute majority]], larger than the one the former major (Luis Díaz Alperi) had, while the oposition (Socialist Party) reduced their popular support.

At the foot of the main staircase of the City Hall Building (''[[Ayuntamiento]]'') is the zero point (''cota cero''), used as the point of reference for measuring the height above or below sea level of any point in Spain, due to the marginal tidal variations of the Mediterranean sea in Alicante.&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.alicante-ayto.es/cultura/edificios_singulares/ayuntamiento_alicante.html Ayuntamiento de Alicante, Edificios Singulares] {{es icon}}&lt;/ref&gt;

==Climate==
Alicante enjoys a [[Mediterranean climate]] with mild temperatures throughout the year and little rain, concentrated in equinoctial periods. On average the temperature ranges between {{convert|16.8|°C|0|abbr=on}} and {{convert|6.2|°C|0|abbr=on}} in January and {{convert|30.6|°C|0|abbr=on}} and {{convert|20.4|°C|0|abbr=on}} in August, with an average annual temperature of {{convert|17.8|°C|0|abbr=on}}. Daily oscillations in temperature are very small due to the influence of the sea, although occasional periods of Westerly wind can result in temperature ranges in excess of {{convert|15|°C|0|abbr=on}}. Annual oscillations in temperature are also small meaning that winters are mild and summers are warm.

The average amount of rainfall is {{convert|336|mm|1|abbr=on}} per year. September and October are the wettest months due to torrential rain caused by the [[cold drop]], which can reach over 200&amp;nbsp;mm in a single 24 hour period causing severe flooding. Because of this irregularity, only 37 rainy days are observed on average per year, and the annual number of sunshine hours is 2,864.

The record maximum temperature of {{convert|41.4|°C|0|abbr=on}} was observed in Alicante on 4 July 1994. The record minimum temperature of {{convert|-4.6|°C|0|abbr=on}} was registered on 12 February 1956. The worst flooding in modern history occurred on 30 September 1997 when {{convert|270.2|mm|1|abbr=on}} of rainfall fell within six hours.

